    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1972-06-14T19:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1972-06-14T19:00:00-05:00" n="329"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d329">
                <head>329. Note From the <gloss type="from">Soviet Leadership</gloss> to President
                        <persName type="to">Nixon</persName>
                    <note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d329fn1">Source: National Archives, Nixon
                        Presidential Materials, <gloss target="#t_NSC1">NSC</gloss> Files, Box 494,
                        President’s Trip Files, <persName corresp="#p_DAF1"
                            >Dobrynin</persName>/<persName corresp="#p_KHA1">Kissinger</persName>,
                        1972, Vol. 12. Top Secret. A handwritten notation on the note indicates that
                            <persName corresp="#p_VYM1">Vorontsov</persName> handed it to <persName
                            corresp="#p_KHA1">Kissinger</persName> at 8:15 p.m. on June 14.
                        According to a transcript of a telephone conversation between <persName
                            corresp="#p_KHA1">Kissinger</persName> and <persName corresp="#p_DAF1"
                            >Dobrynin</persName> at 7:52 p.m., <persName corresp="#p_KHA1"
                            >Kissinger</persName> asked <persName corresp="#p_DAF1"
                            >Dobrynin</persName> to send <persName corresp="#p_VYM1"
                            >Vorontsov</persName> over. <persName corresp="#p_DAF1"
                            >Dobrynin</persName> replied, “Ok. If you have a question or anything
                        please tell him then and then if you have some comment to make, then I will
                        make a report or—but I am really prepared to come anytime to you after if
                        you need or tomorrow morning.” (Ibid., <persName corresp="#p_KHA1"
                            >Kissinger</persName> Office Files, Box 14, Chronological File)</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Moscow</placeName>, <date
                            ana="#date_undated-inferred-from-document-content" calendar="gregorian"
                            type="received-date" when="1972-06-14T20:00:00-04:00"
                        >undated</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <list>
                    <label>1.</label>
                    <item>The Soviet side proceeds on the basis that the aggregate levels of <gloss
                            target="#t_SLBM1">SLBM</gloss> launchers, established for the sides by
                        the Protocol to the Interim Agreement,<note n="2" xml:id="d329fn2">
                            <ref target="#d318">Document 318</ref>.</note> cover <gloss
                            target="#t_SLBM1">SLBM</gloss> launchers of any type, including those on
                        the diesel-powered submarines (known in the <gloss target="#t_US1"
                            >US</gloss> as “G-Class” submarines). In this connection ballistic
                        missile launchers on older submarines may be used for the purposes of
                        replacement as defined in the Protocol to the Interim Agreement.</item>
                    <pb facs="1003" n="968" xml:id="pg_968"/>
                    <label>2.</label>
                    <item>The Soviet side also proceeds on the basis that a first “replacement”
                        submarine for the <gloss target="#t_USSR1">USSR</gloss> is that first modern
                        ballistic missile submarine that carries <gloss target="#t_SLBM1"
                            >SLBM</gloss> launchers in excess of the 740 <gloss target="#t_SLBM1"
                            >SLBM</gloss>s on nuclear-powered submarines refered to in the Protocol.
                        When such submarine begins its sea trial and for all subsequent ones, the
                        dismantling of an equal number of older <gloss target="#t_ICBM1"
                            >ICBM</gloss>s or older <gloss target="#t_SLBM1">SLBM</gloss>s must have
                        begun and will be completed in the shortest possible agreed period of
                        time.</item>
                </list>
                <p>As regards the question of specifying the commencement time of the replacement
                    process, the Soviet side proceeds on the basis that national means of control
                    make it possible to determine the commencement of sea trial of a new ballistic
                    missile submarine, and, according to the agreed statement of the <gloss
                        target="#t_USSR1">USSR</gloss> and the <gloss target="#t_USA1">USA</gloss>
                    delegations in Helsinki, notification thereof will be accomplished under
                    procedures to be agreed in the standing consultative commission. In view of the
                    above, additional specification in regard to this question is not required at
                    this time.</p>
                <p>The Soviet side proceeds on the basis that a “modern” ballistic missile on a
                    submarine is a missile of the type which is deployed on nuclear-powered
                    submarines commissioned in the Soviet Union since 1965.</p>
            </div>
